The '''Kaiser effect''' is a phenomenon observed in geology and material science that describes a pattern of [[acoustic emission]] or [[seismicity]] in a body of rock or other material subjected to repeated cycles of mechanical [[Stress (mechanics)|stress]]. In material that exhibits an initial seismic response under a certain load, the Kaiser effect describes the absence of acoustic emission or seismic events until that load is exceeded. The Kaiser effect results from discontinuities (fractures) created in material during previous steps that do not move, expand, or propagate until the former stress is exceeded. 
<ref name="ndt-ed">{{cite web|url=http://www.ndt-ed.org/EducationResources/CommunityCollege/Other%20Methods/AE/AE_Theory-Sources.htm|title=AE Sources|publisher=ndt-ed.org|accessdate=2014-12-13}}</ref>
<ref name="gua">{{cite journal|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0167278901003062|title=The effect of disorder on the fracture nucleation process|publisher=springer|accessdate=2016-03-23|doi=10.1016/S0167-2789(01)00306-2|volume=158|journal=Physica D: Nonlinear Phenomena|pages=83–104|year=2001|last1=Ciliberto|first1=S.|last2=Guarino|first2=A.|last3=Scorretti|first3=R.|arxiv=cond-mat/0108514|bibcode=2001PhyD..158...83C}}</ref>
<ref name="google">{{cite book|title=Infrastructure Health in Civil Engineering: Theory and Components|author1=Ettouney, M.M.|author2=Alampalli, S.|date=2011|publisher=Taylor & Francis|isbn=9780849320408|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3VePAhhi_OsC|page=424|accessdate=2014-12-13}}</ref> It is named for Joseph Kaiser, who first studied this behavior in materials in the 1950s.<ref name="ndt">{{cite web|url=http://www.ndt.net/ndtaz/content.php?id=471|title=http://www.ndt.net/ndtaz/content.php?id=471|publisher=ndt.net|accessdate=2014-12-13}}</ref> 

== Observed examples of the Kaiser effect ==
=== Borehole seismicity ===
Induced seismicity associated with fluid pumping in boreholes and wells often exhibits the Kaiser effect, whereby seismicity may be observed shortly following an initial fluid injection, but further seismicity is limited if the fluid flow remains at a constant pressure.<ref>Zang, A., Oye, V., Jousset, P., Deichmann, N., Gritto, R., McGarr, A., ... & Bruhn, D. (2014). Analysis of induced seismicity in geothermal reservoirs–An overview. Geothermics, 52, 6-21.</ref> If the fluid pressure at the injection site is later increased, renewed seismicity may be observed due to the greater ease of fracturing caused by higher pore fluid pressure in the rock.

=== Volcanic systems ===
The Kaiser effect has also been observed in relation to recharge of [[Magma chamber|magma chambers]] below active volcanic systems.<ref>Heimisson, E. R., Einarsson, P., Sigmundsson, F., & Brandsdóttir, B. (2015). Kilometer‐scale Kaiser effect identified in Krafla volcano, Iceland. Geophysical Research Letters, 42(19), 7958-7965.</ref> 

